      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Power of Green</hl1>
      </hedline>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Friedman's message to go ''green'' was most welcome, with one exception: after espousing the benefits of the free market, he goes on to recommend massive government intervention in the energy market to promote nuclear power. To be consistent, government action should adhere to his original premise of limiting overall carbon emissions and then letting market forces determine the best means of achieving those limits.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Friedman's message to go ''green'' was most welcome, with one exception: after espousing the benefits of the free market, he goes on to recommend massive government intervention in the energy market to promote nuclear power. To be consistent, government action should adhere to his original premise of limiting overall carbon emissions and then letting market forces determine the best means of achieving those limits.</p>
        <p>Steven H. Smith  San Francisco</p>
      </block>
